---
import BaseLayout from "../../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
import FlavorTabs from "../../../components/FlavorTabs.astro";
import ModuleHero from "../../../components/module/ModuleHero.astro";
import ModuleScenario from "../../../components/module/ModuleScenario.astro";
import ModuleFlowDiagram from "../../../components/module/ModuleFlowDiagram.astro";
import ModuleFooterNav from "../../../components/module/ModuleFooterNav.astro";
import ModuleRecap from "../../../components/module/ModuleRecap.astro";
import { flavor as gcp } from "../../../data/flavors/gcp";
import { flavor as aws } from "../../../data/flavors/aws";
import { flavor as azure } from "../../../data/flavors/azure";
import { flavor as oss } from "../../../data/flavors/oss";

const moduleId = "45-evaluation";
const entries = {
  gcp: gcp[moduleId],
  aws: aws[moduleId],
  azure: azure[moduleId],
  oss: oss[moduleId],
};
---

<BaseLayout title="45 · Evaluation">
  <article>
    <ModuleHero moduleId={moduleId}>
      <p>
        Module 35 gave you recall@k and precision@k against a handful of hand-checked queries. Evaluation turns that
        habit into a system: a golden dataset, automated metrics, and a gate in CI — so "the new prompt feels better"
        becomes a number that either passed or didn't.
      </p>
    </ModuleHero>

    <ModuleScenario moduleId={moduleId} />

    <ModuleFlowDiagram moduleId={moduleId} />

    <h2>Golden datasets</h2>
    <p>
      A <strong>golden dataset</strong> is 20 or more labeled question/answer pairs, ideally drawn from real user
      questions plus the documents ingested back in Module 10. Each row needs a question, the reference context (which
      chunks should be retrieved), and a reference answer. Without this set, every later metric has nothing to compare
      against — it's the fixture the rest of the module runs on.
    </p>

    <h2>RAGAS-style metrics</h2>
    <p>
      <strong>Faithfulness</strong> checks whether every claim in the generated answer is actually supported by the
      retrieved context — it catches hallucination even when the answer sounds confident. <strong>Answer
      relevance</strong> checks whether the response actually addresses the question asked, independent of whether
      it's grounded. <strong>Context precision</strong> and <strong>context recall</strong> score the retrieval half:
      precision asks whether the retrieved chunks were relevant, recall asks whether the relevant chunks were
      retrieved at all. Together they separate "retrieval failed" from "generation failed" instead of leaving you with
      one blended "the answer was wrong" verdict.
    </p>

    <h2>LLM-as-judge and calibration</h2>
    <p>
      Most of these metrics are themselves computed by asking another LLM to score the response — an
      <strong>LLM-as-judge</strong>. That's cheap and scales to hundreds of examples, but a judge model has its own
      blind spots and biases. The fix is calibration: periodically sample judge scores and compare them against a
      human's own rating on the same examples. If they disagree often, the judge prompt (or judge model) needs work
      before you trust it to gate anything.
    </p>

    <h2>Regression evals in CI</h2>
    <p>
      Once you trust the metrics, wire them into CI as an <strong>eval-gated deploy</strong>: every change to the
      prompt, retrieval pipeline, or model re-runs the golden dataset, and the build fails if faithfulness or context
      recall drops below a threshold. This is the same discipline as a unit test suite, aimed at model quality instead
      of code correctness — and it's what turns Module 55's traces from "interesting logs" into "the thing that stops
      a bad release."
    </p>

    <h2>Try it in your flavor</h2>
    <FlavorTabs moduleId={moduleId} entries={entries} />

    <h2>Pitfalls</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>Trusting LLM-as-judge scores without ever checking them against human labels — an uncalibrated judge can be confidently wrong.</li>
      <li>Building a golden dataset once and never updating it as real user questions drift from your original assumptions.</li>
      <li>Blending faithfulness and context recall into one "quality score" — you lose the ability to tell whether retrieval or generation caused a regression.</li>
      <li>Adding an eval gate to CI but never lowering the threshold as the pipeline improves, so it stops catching anything.</li>
    </ul>
  </article>
  <ModuleRecap moduleId={moduleId} />
  <ModuleFooterNav moduleId={moduleId} />
</BaseLayout>
